The behavior you're seeing isn't a bug in your code — it's how browsers handle HTML injection by design.
When React renders HTML through dangerouslySetInnerHTML (or any element.innerHTML = ... assignment), the HTML5 spec explicitly says that <script> elements inserted this way will not execute. The parser builds the DOM nodes but deliberately skips running them. So your <div>s appear, but the script that generates your data and curves never fires. Same root cause likely explains the CSS: if your styles live in a <head> block or a <link> tag and you're only injecting the <body> fragment, those get stripped; and relative <link href="..."> paths won't resolve against your .NET app's routes.
Since your screenshot shows a full self-contained page (data setup, gauss(), product curves — it needs its JS to function), the cleanest fix is to stop injecting it into your React tree and instead render it in an iframe with srcDoc. That gives the content its own document context where scripts run and CSS applies normally, and it's isolated from your chat app's styles so nothing leaks either direction:
jsxfunction HtmlPreview({ html }) {
  return (
    <iframe
      srcDoc={html}
      sandbox="allow-scripts"   // scripts run; isolated origin
      style={{ width: "100%", height: "600px", border: "none" }}
      title="rendered-content"
    />
  );
}
A couple of notes on the sandbox attribute: allow-scripts lets the inline JS execute, while omitting allow-same-origin keeps the iframe in a unique origin so it can't touch your parent app — a sensible default for content arriving through a chat window. If the page also needs to load external resources, make sure those are absolute URLs since relative paths resolve against the iframe's (blank) base.
If you specifically need the content inline in the same DOM (for example, so it inherits your chat's styling), then iframe isn't an option and you'd have to re-execute the scripts manually after injection — the browser won't do it for you:
jsxuseEffect(() => {
  const el = containerRef.current;
  el.innerHTML = html;
  el.querySelectorAll("script").forEach((old) => {
    const s = document.createElement("script");
    [...old.attributes].forEach((a) => s.setAttribute(a.name, a.value));
    s.textContent = old.textContent;
    old.replaceWith(s);
  });
}, [html]);
But this runs the injected JS in your main page context with full access to your app — only do it if you fully trust the HTML source. For a chat window rendering arbitrary page source, the sandboxed iframe is the safer and more reliable choice.
One question that determines which path fits: is this HTML coming from a trusted internal source, or could it be arbitrary/user-supplied content flowing through the chat? That mostly decides iframe-sandbox vs. inline.
